[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Examining JVM and H2 API**\n\nI'm thinking about the agent on JVM and how it should record the exact class or method from the public H2 API. I wonder if the native image config gets generated during the test? It seems like they haven’t committed the generated resources except for serialization, and external Forge merges could be a factor. Also, I should consider the potential for a public test class with a nested public static class. This exploration seems important!\n\n**Evaluating test class rules**\n\nI’m noticing that the test file needs to map to a dynamic class in a one-to-one way, which seems okay. I need to remember the rule about not using $ in test class or file names. Although inner nested class names generate a $, it looks like top-level classes are what we should stick to in order to avoid extra dynamic class files. I wonder about the implications for inner or anonymous classes mentioned.\n\n**Exploring class structuring and reflection**\n\nI’m considering that an inner helper class can be compiled with $, which might be okay, but it feels safer to avoid reflecting on nested classes. I need to clarify things for constructors or methods, maybe using JDK public classes to bypass metadata issues. But then, if the reflection on those classes isn't complete, it could lead to problems. \n\nI wonder if I can define a top-level non-public helper class in the same Java file without using $. That might work!\n\n**Assessing accessibility and reflection**\n\nI need to ensure that the class is accessible because using reflection with newInstance might throw an IllegalAccess error if the class isn't public. I wonder about making it public, but since Java allows only one public top-level class per file, that complicates things. I could consider using existing public test classes, but they may not have suitable constructors or methods. \n\nMaybe creating a new public top-level class in a separate file breaks the one-to-one rule for dynamic class files, so that might not be a good idea. Using the UtilsTest class with a default public no-arg constructor seems like a better option since it’s public!\n\n**Implementing Utils for method calls**\n\nI’m considering using `Utils.newInstance(UtilsTest.class.getName())`, which should return an instance of UtilsTest. This allows me to call methods on this instance without needing to nest anything. It's nice because it simplifies accessing the public helper methods directly from the created instance. I think this approach keeps things clean and straightforward! Plus, it avoids dealing with the extra complexity of nested classes, which is always a plus.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_013a99f7a9f718620169f999e02f0881929fabecf1e71bbfc8\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp-Zn2ZkX6v3GD_Uk4eNJx26hRIRA1nixYHOMUfqxdQK3DLhDmkgqyv5LOBVA4I9G57QN-1TIkT7righ7Dx55x3iexcChbKPldDj89eN8cOub6wTL4SRM4OMn5hKhvNkavSNA3pitendy36w_v1NiamrsLLZnmviZ5fNLer3eSBXgX0Sf2mgwxvf1fkL1ZTqW3BotYLYqaRpCiZtRVnWkSB_Xrr9cRtMbyFnW5AgguPag54YYy45tre2ZVT2WDvJ43EfZR1YXbbxt1eTRStfXg1uu9vyMsUet3JXf_gJ-2-5GBYndso11_mN-kdlg5-yUvPGHBB6-1Q0RiGUfGTcp1jgx_kNblYGbCVlxr7DZJXRVSl6P0D90WKHKm6kmjwPOkvMzHJqmdBayp8GIGRjrRT2rK0B5l7zs4psvSijrfgb60ZxyrA-Tdia3qZaUtOAFJnaO7hssB9yYHmCeIUctgK-ogQeJg7PvxJwKqZe1aucvQEiOaMVIUEfq5APX5ALWyqPHfPNgpXw0eNQiRQM8FqPud3aXXZIF6cz_s1A15lW_XfaIKwLI_0qESLAt61c-vQJ_zegtbjKIiSibibC5tVkJ7xVDcXCtXCxUMVgTcsgYr_j3iwzouDStsO4vrOVXSptS3xHbMQEZNa79ob6M5oaIgAMDjFVn6JH-wAifYMbMWuOtDS7jYnBD92uy3E3kAXAhGCIQvG5z54m-cGmA0VzEs_JVxaeYWaWhslrZ2XfAWkfOy2crfUiEdyfXBeStEwt-BGY0c71h4ZR--UH4rMfaBfK1T4pwrNRfw4IfCJyxcOF07lp0lrvYRZgeBBcswd_D-uG86p5DIsBtgzX0Z_iaLhN3oSdT_Pyb5VyhTjyOTQ1JI5YXu6X_wHVBmS0v0x6bhVvAqAB3SeBGX1FKLwNd--PSAlK2AtytldYCKH16wUFU0XxU72eV3B3AVel9vt-iPC9bsTD0FWIKYdEgs0WQ1rsi-GKCFcskLaBKDjSZb0JqKSfUnWgzrJUrHF05sCx7lGUXWjUv7d_tnk3PiCwp3ZP-m9MLMtpMZeP76DpZ8WC2j-dNfT-yCMlb2_Afqyhubm4ytxweMzLIOnUy3lECq